Obviously not. The monster only roared, trying to ram directly into Sasilin. Praise heaven, although Sasilin was large in size, it was still relatively agile and managed to dodge in time. However, Nisi couldn't help but let out a shrill scream, nearly sliding off Sasilin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill them?" Nisi shouted.
"Target their heads!"
"This is too difficult!"
Sasilin roared and circled, flying towards the mountain he called home. The black monster followed closely, but when it was attacked by flames from behind, it seemed a bit flustered. This monster hadn't realized it now had another opponent. Sasilin slowed down, then used its tail to strike the monster's head forcefully, causing it to veer off course and become even more panicked.
The monster roared, hissing in its throat, flying straight up, continuously spewing something into the air. Suddenly, everything around turned pitch black, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky and replacing it with eternal darkness.
Sasilin's vision went dark, and he tried to retreat, but found himself hitting the treetops and falling to the ground. The monster seemed to know exactly where Sasilin had landed and flew directly toward him, bringing that cloud with it.
"Tayuk!" Tenuk shouted as he flew out of the cloud, beginning to circle, trying to find Nisi and Sasilin in the darkness below. "What should we do? Kayer...? Kayer, where are you?"
Nisi struggled to stand up. She felt sure she must have broken several bones, but her strange, unnatural healing ability was already at work. Sasilin, on the other hand, lay weakly on the ground, propped up against a tree he had knocked over. Nisi strained to walk toward Sasilin, but her vision was pitch black and she could hardly see anything. Shadows everywhere were filled with terrifying screams.
A terrifying club-like tail slammed down, flipping Nisi onto the ground. She noticed the tail was swinging wildly, but its target didn't seem to be her. Nisi managed to see the monster roaring, using its claws to frantically scratch the shadows it created. Something darted through the darkness, ready to stab the monster.
Suddenly, a gunshot pierced the air, and the monster immediately fell silent, lying still on the ground. The surrounding darkness dissipated, revealing the truth. Kayer stood on the monster's corpse, holding a rifle, panting heavily.
"That was... one of the strangest shadow leaps I've ever done... Tan-to Kato Oroon..." Kayer panted. For some reason, his eyes glowed black, and dark energy surged within him. But just as Kayer began to speak, his organic armor returned to its original color, and his eyes turned back to their normal yellow.
After a while, Nisi finally understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayer possessed eerie shadow abilities, but he rarely used them because most people believed such abilities were extremely evil and terrifying. However, Nisi did not know that Kayer could use these abilities in any darkness. Moreover, from Kayer's reaction, it seemed that he was also quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay?" Nisi couldn't help asking.
"I'm fine. I killed that thing, and I'll be back to myself soon." Kayer looked at his "masterpiece," and at that moment, Tenuk landed beside him, reverting to his original Spartast form.
Now, the monster was no longer moving, and they could take a good look at what it really was. Its skin was dark and glossy, covered in a layer of sticky liquid that clung tightly to the monster's body. It had four wings and four legs, each ending in long, slender claws, and its skull sported two straight horns.
Before Tenuk and Kayer could ask what this was, a monster screamed and leaped out from nearby bushes. Just then, a familiar car crashed into the monster's side, sliding for a distance before stopping at Nisi's feet. Nisi didn't hesitate, grabbing the shotgun and firing a shot directly at the monster's head, killing it instantly.
"Oh...," Revtvik muttered from the driver's seat, then clumsily turned off the engine and climbed down from the truck. "Uh, I didn't mean to. Are you guys okay?"
"You missed all the action!" Tenuk said with a tongue-click. "Where have you been?"
"Leaving me behind was your fault. I tried to catch up as fast as I could...," Revtvik sighed. "May I ask, what are these terrifying creatures?"
Revtvik's question was answered by Sasilin, who had already stood up. He was covered in wounds and scratch marks, looking a bit dazed, but his injuries didn't seem severe.
"You killed the Corrupters! Those infected monsters. When corruption attacked your gods, these creatures were left behind here."
"Tenuk stammered, 'You mean... we... helped kill the terrifying god-monsters?'"
"Yes, that's right. There might be more Corrupters. But I can't shoot them in the head. I don't have a gun. And two against one is unfair, isn't it?" Sasilin walked up to Kayer and patted his head. "Thanks, little guy. You remind me of my old friend Alkardin. Only you're not as ruthless, and you don't have his power to destroy the universe."
"Uh... Thanks... I think..." Kayer shrugged. "So, uh, did we finish the task?"
Nisi shrugged, picked up her camera, and took several photos of the monsters she was sure were dead. Then, she pulled out her favorite dagger—the exquisite Deathscythe—and began cutting one of the monster's horns, then moved to cut the other. However, just as Nisi finished cutting, the monsters suddenly started burning from within, turning into ashes almost instantly. The horns Nisi had chopped off also turned to ashes.
"Well... This does have its pros and cons..." Nisi sighed. "At least I still have the photos."
